\subsection{Commit details}

For a single commit we use [[git show]], which produces the
commit header, the full message (containing the captured I/O),
and the unified diff (showing the code that changed)---all in a
single subprocess call.

A teacher reviewing student work typically wants to see
\emph{what changed} before reading the run metadata (script
name, arguments, captured I/O).
The default [[git show]] order is header, message, diff; we
rearrange to header, diff, message so that code changes appear
first.

The [[git show]] output always starts with metadata lines
(commit hash, author, date) followed by a blank line, then the
indented commit message, then the diff.
Both reordering and filtering need to locate these three sections,
so we extract the boundary-finding into a single function.

The header ends at the first blank line.
The diff starts at the first [[diff --git]] line; when no diff is
present---for example, the initial commit that only records a run
without any file changes---[[diff_start]] is [[None]].

<<helper functions>>=
def parse_show_sections(lines):
    """Find section boundaries in ``git show`` output.

    Returns ``(header_end, diff_start)`` where
    ``header_end`` is the index of the first blank line and
    ``diff_start`` is the index of the first ``diff --git``
    line, or ``None`` if no diff is present.
    """
    header_end = 0
    for i, line in enumerate(lines):
        if line == "":
            header_end = i
            break

    diff_start = None
    for i, line in enumerate(lines):
        if line.startswith("diff --git "):
            diff_start = i
            break

    return header_end, diff_start
@

<<helper functions>>=
def reorder_commit_detail(detail):
    """Reorder ``git show`` output: header, diff, message.

    Moves the unified diff before the commit message so that
    code changes are visible first in the viewer.
    """
    lines = detail.split("\n")
    header_end, diff_start = parse_show_sections(lines)

    if diff_start is None:
        return detail

    header = lines[:header_end + 1]
    message = lines[header_end + 1:diff_start]
    diff = lines[diff_start:]

    return "\n".join(header + diff + [""] + message)
@

We load details lazily---only when the user navigates to a
particular commit---to keep the viewer responsive even for
repositories with hundreds of commits.


\subsection{Filtering learnlog's own runs}
\label{sec:filter-learnlog}

When the [[learnlog]] CLI is invoked (\eg [[learnlog play]]), the
package's [[__init__.py]] logs the invocation as a run block---just
like any student program.
These self-referential entries clutter the playback with tool usage
that is not part of the student's development.

Since multiple runs without code changes are appended to the same
commit (separated by [[\n\n---\n\n]], see \cref{gitrepo}), a single
commit can contain both student runs and learnlog runs.
We therefore filter at the run-block level within each commit message,
not at the commit level.

The separator [[\n\n---\n\n]] is safe to split on because the
section markers within a run block ([[--- I/O ---]],
[[--- exception ---]]) always have additional text after the dashes.

<<helper functions>>=
def filter_learnlog_runs(message):
    """Remove learnlog CLI run blocks from a commit message.

    Splits on the ``---`` block separator and removes blocks
    whose header starts with ``Run: learnlog``.
    Returns the filtered message, which may be empty if all
    blocks were learnlog runs.
    """
    BLOCK_SEP = "\n\n---\n\n"
    blocks = message.split(BLOCK_SEP)
    filtered = [
        b for b in blocks
        if not b.lstrip().startswith("Run: learnlog")
    ]
    return BLOCK_SEP.join(filtered)
@

Let's verify that filtering works for mixed, student-only, and
learnlog-only commit messages:

<<test functions>>=
def test_filter_learnlog_runs_removes_block():
    from learnlog.cli import filter_learnlog_runs
    msg = (
        "Run: hello.py (none)\n\nScript: hello.py\n"
        "\n\n---\n\n"
        "Run: learnlog play\n\nScript: learnlog\n"
    )
    result = filter_learnlog_runs(msg)
    assert "hello.py" in result
    assert "learnlog" not in result

def test_filter_learnlog_runs_preserves_student():
    from learnlog.cli import filter_learnlog_runs
    msg = "Run: hello.py (none)\n\nScript: hello.py\n"
    assert filter_learnlog_runs(msg) == msg

def test_filter_learnlog_runs_all_learnlog():
    from learnlog.cli import filter_learnlog_runs
    msg = (
        "Run: learnlog play\n\nScript: learnlog\n"
        "\n\n---\n\n"
        "Run: learnlog export\n\nScript: learnlog\n"
    )
    result = filter_learnlog_runs(msg)
